<DOC><DOCNO> AP881201-0109 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-88 1329EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Shuttle-CrewThumbnails     12-01 0615</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Shuttle-Crew Thumbnails,0637</SECOND><HEAD>Atlantis Crewmen At a Glance</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here are brief sketches of the fivemilitary astronauts assigned to Atlantis:   NAVY CMDR. ROBERT L. GIBSON: Commander. Gibson also commandedColumbia on a January 1986 flight that was the last mission beforethe Challenger explosion and was a pilot aboard Challenger on hisfirst flight in February 1984.   Gibson, 42, was born in Cooperstown, N.Y., but considersLakewood, Calif., his hometown. He graduated from CaliforniaPolytechnic State University with a degree in aeronauticalengineering.   In 1969, Gibson entered active duty with the Navy and later flewcombat missions in Southeast Asia. He was selected as an astronautin January 1978.   Gibson is married to Dr. Rhea Seddon, who also is an astronautand has flown on one previous shuttle flight. He has two children,Julie 12, and Paul, 6.   He is a member of an all-astronaut rock 'n' roll band calledMAX-Q, the abbreviation for the point in the shuttle's ascent whenaerodynamic stress is at its maximum. The band does informal gigs inthe Clear Lake area south of Houston.</TEXT><TEXT>   AIR FORCE LT. COL. GUY S. GARDNER: Pilot. Gardner, an astronautsince May 1980, is making his first shuttle flight.   Gardner, 40, was born in Alta Vista, Va., but considersAlexandria, Va., his hometown. He received a bachelor's degree inengineering sciences, astronautics and mathematics from the U.S. AirForce Academy, and a master's degree in astronautics from PurdueUniversity.   He flew 177 combat missions in Southeast Asia in 1972 whilestationed in Thailand and later was an Air Force test pilot and aninstructor test pilot.   Gardner and his wife, Linda, have three children, Jennifer, 15,Sarah, 11, and Jason, 10.</TEXT><TEXT>   AIR FORCE COL. RICHARD M. MULLANE: Mission specialist. Mullanefirst flew on Discovery's maiden voyage in August 1984. Theseven-day mission featured the deployment of three satellites.   Mullane, 43, was born in Wichita Falls, Texas, but he grew up inAlbuquerque, N.M., where he also attended high school. He is agraduate of West Point and earned his master's degree inaeronautical engineering from the Air Force Institute of Technology.   He completed 150 combat missions in Vietnam as a weapon systemoperator. In July 1976, he was assigned as a flight test weaponsystem operator at Eglin Air Force Base, Fla.   Mullane was selected as an astronaut in January 1978. He and hiswife, Donna, have three children, twins Patrick and Michele, 20, andLaura, 17.</TEXT><TEXT>   AIR FORCE LT. COL. JERRY L. ROSS: Mission specialist. During hisfirst flight aboard Atlantis in November 1985, Ross twice walked inspace while demonstrating construction techniques for a spacestation.   Ross, 40, born in Crown Point, Ind., received a bachelor's and amaster's degree in mechanical engineering from Purdue University.While with the Air Force, he worked extensively in testing the B-1bomber.   In February 1979, Ross was assigned to the Payload OperationsDivision at NASA's Johnson Space Center as a payload officer-flightcontroller and was responsible for integrating payloads into thespace shuttle.   Ross was selected as an astronaut in May 1980. He and his wife,Karen, have two children, Amy, 17, and Scott, 16.</TEXT><TEXT>   NAVY CMDR. WILLIAM M. SHEPHERD. Mission specialist. Shepherd, whowas selected as an astronaut in May 1984, is making his firstshuttle flight.   Shepherd, 39, was born in Oak Ridge, Tenn., but he grew up in theWashington D.C. area. He received a bachelor's degree in aerospaceengineering from the U.S. Naval Academy in 1971, and the degree ofocean engineer and a master's in mechanical engineering from theMassachusetts Institute of Technology. He is single.</TEXT></DOC>